Students are expected to understand the multidisciplinary nature of environmental management, learn the various measures (regulatory, economic, technological) available, and aware of different stakeholders' needs and the constraints in environmental protection.

Students should be able to:

1. understand the socio-economic causes of environmental problems;
2. view environment as a site for conflict and environmental solutions for conflict resolution;
3. sustainability as the core conceptual principle of environmental protection;
4. appreciate that environmental protection can be achieved by changes in environmental attitudes and ethics;
5. sole use of technologies cannot eliminate environmental problems, but integration of technical and nontechnical measures (incl voluntary corporate environmental management) in environmental protection; environmental protection strategies and their inadequa cies in tackling local environmental problems.

