Students are expected to attain the knowledge about how urbanisation affects the local climate and the underlying processes. They should also be able to:
1. describe the scientific processes and explain the theories of how urbanisation alters local climate;
2. explain the physical mechanisms governing the formation of urban climatic phenomena;
3. conduct numerical modelling and field experiments of urban climatic processes; and
4. understand the practical implications of urban climatology on climate-sensitive urban planning and design.

Students completing this course are expected to:

1. understand the theory and principles behind the methods and techniques used in environmental impact assessment (EIA);
2. appreciate the processes and requirements of EIA in Hong Kong;
3. become familiar with the protocols and procedures of EIA in Hong Kong.

Students completing this course are expected to:

1. obtain a first hand understanding of how Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) works in Hong Kong by reviewing and critically evaluating existing Hong Kong EIA reports;
2. gain hands-on experiences on how some EIA protocols are carried out;
3. develop the practical skills of doing an EIA by getting involved in actual preparation of a project profile, study brief and by actually carrying out a small scale EIA project;
4. learn from the experiences of front-line practitioners of EIA in Hong Kong by engaging in sharing and discussion with them during guest presentations;
5. strengthen their communication skills through oral presentation and report writing.

